<main>
  <center><h3>About Edigaul and Rohkshe</h3></center>
  <section class="pageText">
    <p>
      Edigaul [<i>EH-dih-gawl</i>] is an abugida I created about a year ago for a fictional language I've been creating called Rohkshe [<i>RAWK-shee</i>] which itself is a language from a fictional world I've been developing for more years than I can remember. Besides Rohkshe, Edigaul is also used in the Azin [<i>Æ-zihn</i>] language, though I have not developed that language at all.
    </p>
  </section>

  <center><h4>What is an abugida?</h4></center>
  <section class="pageText">
    <p>
      An abugida is a writing system similar to an alphabet. Before describing what an abugida is, it's best if we define exactly what an alphabet is. First, in a spoken language, we have consonants and vowels. You know what those are, presumably, so no need to explain them. Second, in a writing system, we have letters. A letter is a symbol used to denote a sound in a language. In an alphabet, each consonant and each vowel gets their own letter. In the English alphabet, vowels letters are complicated. One vowel letter, or multiples in a row, can denote a variety of different sounds. Consonant letters in English are a bit more consistent, though they can have their exceptions, too.
    </p>
    <p>
      Vowels and consonants in an abugida are represented by letters differently than they are in an alphabet. In an abugida, only consonants are represented by letters, and, like in an alphabet, there is one letter for each consonant. Vowels are represented by markings applied to those consonant letters. Thus, each "unit" in an abugida represents a sequence of vowel sounds and a single consonant.
    </p>
    <p>
      You can learn more about abugidas by reading the 
      <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abugida">Wikipedia article</a>
      about them.
    </p>
  </section>

  <center><h4>How do I read this "Edigaul?"</h4></center>
  <section class="pageText">
    <p>
      First, given a single letter consisting of the central consonant symbol with one vowel marking above it and one vowel marking below it, you would read the letter from top to bottom. This means that you would read the top vowel marking first, then the consonant, and finally the bottom vowel marking. Edigaul is also read left to right, like English.
    </p>
    <p>
      There are 24 consonants symbols in the Edigaul abugida. Each of these consonants has a specific sound associated with it, though that specific sound may vary slightly from dialect to dialect. (For example, in Foothills Rohkshe, the th sound is always voiceless, but in Middlelands Rohkshe, the th sound is always voiced.)
    </p>
    <p>
      There are two special consonant symbols in the Edigaul abugida which are different from the rest. The first is the X, which is called the Xerithi Z. This X letter is pronounced like a Z, and it is not allowed to have any vowel marks attached to it. It cannot take vowel marks and looks drastically different from the other symbols (fun fact, it is the only consonant that cannot be written in one motion) because it comes from an old runic alphabet. The X symbol is only used for words derived from the word Xerith. The second special symbol is the silent placeholder. This symbol is unpronounced and is only used for "lonely" vowel marks, which are vowel marks that do not have any nearby consonants to which they can attach.
    </p>
  </section>
