  <center><h4>How do I write this "Edigaul?"</h4></center>
  <section class="pageText">
    <p>
      First, if you have little experience writing in Edigaul, it is best to start writing a word by writing its consonants in the order they are pronounced. Once that is done, then deal with the process of adding the vowel marks. We won't worry about dealing with silent placeholders for now. You will rarely need to use them except for words which consist of a single vowel sound and no consonants.
    </p>
    <p>
      When adding vowel marks, first recall from the section on reading Edigaul that a vowel mark above a consonant is pronounced before immediately the consonant, and a vowel mark below a consonant is pronounced immediately after it. The first vowels you should place are any vowels that begin or end the word. If the word begins with a vowel, that vowewl mark <i>has</i> to go above the first consonant. Likewise, if the word ends with a vowel, that vowel mark <i>has</i> to go below the last consonant. Then deal with the vowel marks in the middle of the word.
    </p>
    <p>
      Most of the time, you will not need to put more than one vowel between two consonants, but, if there are two vowels between a pair of consonants, then the vowel that comes first must go below the first consonant in the pair, and the vowel that comes second must go above the second consonant in the pair. But, as I said, usually there will only be one vowel between consonants. In this case, there is a series of three rules that will tell you where to place this vowel mark. But, before I can explain these rules, I must differentiate between two types of consonants.
    </p>
    <p>
      In Edigaul, the consonant symbols can be split into two groups: the uptails and the downtails. The tail on a consonant is the line that sticks out of the head of the consonant. The uptail/downtail category of a consonant is not determined by which direction the tail points however. Instead, when writing a consonant (from left to right), if a tail is written with an upward motion, the consonant is an uptail (the k and d symbols, for example). Similarly, if a tail is written with a downward motion, the consonant is a downtail (the s and t symbols, for example).
    </p>
    <p>
      Now that you know the difference between uptails and downtails, I can explain the three rules for placing a single vowel between two consonants. Go through these rules in order, the first rule that matches your scenario is the rule you should follow.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        If the second consonant in the pair is an uptail, place it above that consonant.
      </li>
      <li>
        If the first consonant in the pair is an uptail, but the second is a downtail, place it below the first consonant.
      </li>
      <li>
        If both consonants in the pair are downtails, place it above the second consonant.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Finally, the boundaries between the morphemes of a word are important. A morpheme, if you are unfamiliar, is a unit within a word which has a distinct meaning and cannot be broken into smaller meaningful units. For example, the word "unhelpful" has three morphemes. Those are un, help, and ful. Some morphemes are words on their own while others are not. When writing in Edigaul, the vowels that belong to a morpheme must not be separated from that morpheme. For example, take the word <i>muuthni</i> (ocean). <i>Muuthni</i> has two morphemes, <i>muuh</i> meaning broad, and <i>thni</i> meaning water. By the rules listed above, the uuh mark in <i>muuthni</i> should go above the th symbol, but there is a morpheme boundary in the way! So the uuh mark goes under the m symbol instead.
    </p>
    <p>
      Vowel placement in Edigaul, as you can see, can be extremely complicated. That's why the
      <a href="/tool">Edigaul Text Tool</a> exists! This tool will automatically place all the vowel marks exactly where they should be, and will even add any required silent placeholders.
    </p>
  </section>
